{"title_page": "Amir Garrett", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox MLB player\n|name        = Amir Garrett\n|image       = CINvARI - Amir Garrett (30415071947) (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = Garrett exiting the bullpen in 2018\n|team        = Cincinnati Reds\n|number      = 50\n|position    = [[Pitcher]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1992|5|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Victorville, California|Victorville]], [[California]]\n|bats        = Left\n|throws      = Left\n|debutdate   = April 7\n|debutyear   = 2017\n|debutteam   = Cincinnati Reds\n|debutleague = MLB\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value  = 9\u201313\n|stat2label  = [[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value  = 5.12\n|stat3label  = [[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value  = 212\n|teams       = \n*[[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|2017}}&ndash;present) \n\n}}\n'''Amir Jamal Garrett''' (born May 3, 1992) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Cincinnati Reds]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Garrett ALSO OWNS THE PIRATES AFTER SHOWING OFF HIS MASSIVE MEAT AND CHARGING AND SUCCESSFULLY FIGHTING THE ENTIRE TEAM.\n was drafted by the Reds in 2011 but played [[college basketball]] for the [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball|St. John's Red Storm]] before pursuing a baseball career fully.\n\n==Early years==\nGarrett began his high school career at [[Sierra Vista High School (Spring Valley, Nevada)|Sierra Vista High School]] in [[Spring Valley, Nevada]], before he transferred to [[Leuzinger High School]] in [[Lawndale, California]], for his junior year. He transferred again, to Findlay College Prep in [[Henderson, Nevada]], for his senior year in 2010.<ref name=milb>{{cite web|last=Dykstra |first=Sam |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140515&content_id=75340930&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb |title=Reds' Garrett remains on two-sport path &#124; MiLB.com News &#124; The Official Site of Minor League Baseball |publisher=Milb.com |date=June 14, 2001 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=vmanstuff |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/jul/25/new-findlay-prep-player-amir-garrett-puts-show-aau/ |title=New Findlay Prep player Amir Garrett puts on a show at summer tourney \u2013 Las Vegas Sun News |publisher=Lasvegassun.com |date=July 25, 2010 |accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> Findlay does not have a baseball team. His father convinced him to give baseball another chance, so he held a training session for [[Major League Baseball]] [[scout (sports)|scouts]], in which he threw a [[fastball]] upwards of {{convert|96|mph}}.<ref name=si/> Eligible in the [[2011 Major League Baseball draft]], the [[Cincinnati Reds]] selected Garrett in the 22nd round. He signed with the Reds, receiving a $1&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]] and permission to continue his basketball career.<ref name=nymag/> In the fall of 2011, Garrett enrolled at [[Bridgton Academy]] in Bridgton, Maine, where he played on the basketball team throughout the 2011-12 season, until enrolling at [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]].\n\n==College career==\n[[Image:Amir Garrett for the St. John's Red Storm.jpg|thumb|left|Garrett with [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball|St. John's]] in 2013]]\nHeading into college, Garrett was a four-star basketball recruit, ranked 68th in the country, and the 21st best [[small forward]].<ref name=nymag>{{cite web|last=Giles |first=Matt |url=https://nymag.com/daily/sports/2011/08/garrett-still-intends-to-play-for-st-john-s.html |title=Garrett Still Intends to Play for St. John's \u2013 The Sports Section |publisher=Nymag.com |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> Garrett committed to attend [[St. John's University (New York)|St. John's University]] to play [[college basketball]] for the [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball]] team.<ref name=si>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/luke_winn/06/06/amir-garrett-st-johns-mlb/ |title=Findlay Prep's Amir Garrett choosing between St. John's, MLB - Luke Winn - SI.com |publisher=Sportsillustrated.cnn.com |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/basketball/mens/news/story?id=5816230 |title=EPSNU 100 SF Amir Garrett commits to St. John's. \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2010}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit  = [[Amir Garrett]]\n| position = [[Small forward|SF]]\n| hometown = Los Angeles{{!}}Los Angeles, CA\n| highschool = [[Bridgton Academy]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 6\n| weight = 190\n| 40     = \n| commitdate = 11/17/2010\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars    = 4\n| espn grade = 92\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit End\n| 40               = \n| year             = 2011\n| rivals ref title = St. John's Basketball Commitment List\n| scout ref title  = 2011 St. John's Basketball Commits\n| espn ref title   = ESPN\n| rivals school    = \n| scout s          = \n| espn schoolid    = \n| scout overall    = 72nd\n| rivals overall   = 68th\n| espn overall     = 99th\n| accessdate       = \n| bball            = yes}}\n\nGarrett was ruled ineligible to play for the college basketball team for the fall semester of his freshman year, in the [[2011\u201312 St. John's Red Storm men's basketball team|2011\u201312 season]], due to academic reasons. During that time, he spent the fall semester at Bridgton Academy in North Bridgton ME where he participated in the Fall Baseball program. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/ncb/story/_/id/6974420/st-john-3-players-ruled-ineligible-fall-semester |title=St. John's has 3 players ruled ineligible for fall semester \u2013 ESPN New York |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=September 15, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Greg Logan |url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/college/college-hoops-scoops-1.1620561/amir-garrett-s-growth-spurt-1.3545013 |title=Amir Garrett's growth spurt |publisher=Newsday.com |date=February 21, 2012 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> He was declared eligible in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmov.com/sports/baseball/national-league/136024623.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629144943/http://www.kmov.com/sports/baseball/national-league/136024623.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 29, 2013 |title=Garrett eligible for St. John's &#124; KMOV.com St. Louis |publisher=Kmov.com |date=December 22, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2013 }}</ref> As a freshman, Garrett played 26.9 [[minutes per game]].<ref name=nydn/> After the basketball season, Garrett played baseball for the [[Arizona Reds]] of the [[Rookie-level]] [[Arizona League]] and the [[Billings Mustangs]] of the [[Rookie-level]] [[Pioneer League (baseball)|Pioneer League]], pitching to a 4.05 [[earned run average]] (ERA) with 18 [[strikeout]]s and 13 [[base on balls|walks]] in 20 [[innings pitched]].<ref name=milb/>\n\nAs a sophomore, Garrett started 11 games, averaging 5.4 [[points per game]] and 4.3 [[rebounds per game]] in 20.1 minutes per game.<ref name=nydn/> After the [[2012\u201313 St. John's Red Storm men's basketball team|2012\u201313 college basketball season]], Garrett announced that he was leaving St. John's, with the intention of transferring to another college basketball team.<ref name=nydn>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/college/garrett-leaving-sju-hoops-possibly-pro-baseball-article-1.1306243 |title=Amir Garrett leaving St. John's basketball, Cincinnati Reds prospect could pursue pro baseball career |publisher=NY Daily News |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> He transferred to [[Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball|California State University, Northridge]],<ref>{{cite web|first=C. Trent |last=Rosecrans |url=http://cincinnati.com/blogs/reds/2013/05/08/reds-prospect-amir-garrett-to-continue-his-college-hoops-career/ |title=Reds prospect Amir Garrett to continue his college hoops career &#124; Cincinnati Reds |publisher=Cincinnati.com |date=May 8, 2013 |accessdate=May 16, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517151607/http://www2.cincinnati.com/blogs/reds/2013/05/08/reds-prospect-amir-garrett-to-continue-his-college-hoops-career/ |archivedate=May 17, 2014 }}</ref> and sat out the [[2013\u201314 Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball team|2013\u201314 season]] due to [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] transfer rules.<ref name=milb/> After \"[[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirting]]\" his first year, Garrett withdrew from the Matadors to pursue a pro baseball career.<ref>{{cite web|title=Two-sport star Amir Garrett gives up college hoops for pro baseball|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/two-sport-star-amir-garrett-gives-up-college-hoops-for-pro-baseball/|website=CBSSports.com|accessdate=September 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nGarrett began the 2013 baseball season with Billings, but was promoted to the [[Dayton Dragons]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Midwest League]] in July.<ref>{{cite web|author=MILB.com |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130719&content_id=54058674&fext=.jsp&vkey=pr_t459&sid=t459 |title=Two-Sport Athlete Amir Garrett Joins Dragons &#124; Dayton Dragons News |publisher=Milb.com |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> He finished the season with a 5.15 ERA, 32 strikeouts, and 26 walks in {{frac|57|2|3}} innings. He returned to Dayton for the start of the 2014 season.<ref name=milb/> In August 2014, Garrett decided to quit basketball and withdraw from Cal-State Northridge in order to focus on baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/eye-on-college-basketball/24653309/two-sport-star-amir-garrett-gives-up-college-hoops-for-pro-baseball|title=Two-sport star Amir Garrett gives up college hoops for pro baseball|first=Matt|last=Norlander |work=[[CBS Sports]]|date=August 8, 2014|accessdate=August 14, 2014}}</ref> He had a 7\u20138 record and a 3.65 ERA in 27 games started, and the Reds added him to their [[40-man roster]] after the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.reds.mlb.com/news/article/105793464/reds-prospect-amir-garrett-thriving-since-choosing-baseball-over-basketball|title=Prospect Garrett thriving since choosing baseball: Two-sport star happy with decision to put down basketball, commit to pitching|first=Mark|last=Sheldon|work=MLB.com|date=January 8, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> He began the 2015 season with the [[Daytona Tortugas]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]] (FSL),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/article/20150407/SPORTS/150409568|title=Former hoopster Amir Garrett flourishing after turning full attention to baseball|work=News-JournalOnline.com|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref> and was chosen to represent the Reds at the 2015 [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.reds.mlb.com/news/article/132835982/cincinnati-reds-trio-picked-for-futures-game|title=Cincinnati Reds trio picked for Futures Game|work=Cincinnati Reds|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Garrett finished the 2015 season with a 2.44 ERA and 133 strikeouts for Daytona, and with [[Jacob Faria]], was named the [[Florida State League Pitcher of the Year Award|Co-FSL Pitcher of the Year]].<ref name=pensacola/>\n\nGarrett opened the 2016 season with the [[Pensacola Blue Wahoos]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Southern League (baseball)|Southern League]].<ref name=pensacola>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160425&content_id=174509902&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb|title=Cincinnati Reds prospect Amir Garrett gets better as he goes along for Pensacola Blue Wahoos - MiLB.com News - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|work=MiLB.com|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> The Reds promoted him to the [[Louisville Bats]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[International League]] in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/mlb/reds/2016/06/18/notes-amir-garrett-earns-triple--promotion/86087740/|title=Notes: Amir Garrett earns Triple-A promotion|work=Cincinnati Enquirer|date=June 18, 2016|accessdate=October 17, 2016}}</ref> He was named to appear in the 2016 All-Star Futures Game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/mlb/reds/2016/06/28/notes-amir-garrett-selected-futures-game/86493498/|title=Notes: Amir Garrett selected for Futures Game|work=Cincinnati Enquirer|date=June 28, 2016|accessdate=October 17, 2016}}</ref> He finished 2016 with a 7-8 record and a 2.55 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=607237#/career/R/pitching/2016/ALL|title=Amir Garrett Stats, Highlights, Bio |work=MiLB.com Stats - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|accessdate=October 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGarrett made the Reds' [[Opening Day]] roster in 2017.<ref>http://m.mlb.com/news/article/221408612/amir-garrett-elated-about-making-reds-rotation/</ref> In his Major league debut on April 7 against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Garrett went six shutout innings, giving up just two hits and earning the win in the Reds 2&ndash;0 victory over the Cardinals.\n\nOn May 7, 2017 Garrett was optioned down to Reds AAA affiliate [[Louisville Bats]], RHP Barrett Astin was recalled.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gray|first1=Doug|title=Amir Garrett optioned to Triple-A, recall Barrett Astin|url=http://redsminorleagues.com/2017/05/07/amir-garrett-optioned-triple-recall-barrett-astin/|website=RedsMinorLeagues.com|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref> On May 25, 2017, Garrett was placed on the 10-day disabled list due to right hip inflammation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheldon|first1=Mark|title=Amir Garrett on DL with right hip inflammation|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/232390664/reds-put-pitcher-amir-garrett-on-disabled-list/|publisher=MLB|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref> Garrett was optioned and recalled multiple times during the season. In 14 starts for Louisville he was 2-4 with a 5.72 ERA, and in 16 games (14 starts) for Cincinnati, he compiled a 3-8 record and 7.39 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=607237#/career/R/pitching/2018/ALL|title=Amir Garrett Stats, Highlights, Bio - MiLB.com Stats - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|publisher=MiLB.com|accessdate=May 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGarrett began the 2018 season in the Cincinnati bullpen. In 66 games, he was 1-2 with 71 strikeouts in 63 innings.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn an April 7, 2019 game against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], Garrett was ejected after his role in a bench clearing incident involving [[Chris Archer]], [[Derek Dietrich]], [[Yasiel Puig]], [[David Bell (baseball)|David Bell]], [[Keone Kela]], and [[Felipe V\u00e1zquez]]. Over 3 months later, on July 30 Garrett was once again involved in a bench clearing incident, charging the Pirates dugout and throwing punches at players in the dugout. Garrett was ejected along with Yasiel Puig, [[Francisco Cervelli]], [[Kyle Crick]], Chris Archer, and [[Trevor Williams (baseball)|Trevor Williams]]. This followed after David Bell (who would later go back onto the field during the brawl) was ejected in the bottom of the 8th inning by Larry Vanover for arguing balls and strikes and later in the top of the 9th inning where Reds relief pitcher Jared Hughes and bench coach Freddie Benavides were ejected in the ninth for hitting [[Starling Marte]] with his first pitch.{{cn|date=July 2019}} On August 1, 2019, Garrett was suspended for 8 games.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of multi-sport athletes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=607237|espn=33652|br=g/garream01|fangraphs=14375|brm=garret000ami}}\n*{{Twitter|Amir_Garrett|CountOnAG}}\n*{{Instagram|amir_garrett|CountOnAG}}\n\n{{Cincinnati Reds roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrett, Amir}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:People from Victorville, California]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from California]]\n[[Category:African-American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Findlay Prep alumni]]\n[[Category:St. John's Red Storm men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Reds players]]\n[[Category:Billings Mustangs players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Dayton Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Daytona Tortugas players]]\n[[Category:Pensacola Blue Wahoos players]]\n[[Category:Louisville Bats players]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox MLB player\n|name        = Amir Garrett\n|image       = CINvARI - Amir Garrett (30415071947) (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = Garrett exiting the bullpen in 2018\n|team        = Cincinnati Reds\n|number      = 50\n|position    = [[Pitcher]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1992|5|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Victorville, California|Victorville]], [[California]]\n|bats        = Left\n|throws      = Left\n|debutdate   = April 7\n|debutyear   = 2017\n|debutteam   = Cincinnati Reds\n|debutleague = MLB\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value  = 9\u201313\n|stat2label  = [[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value  = 5.12\n|stat3label  = [[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value  = 212\n|teams       = \n*[[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|2017}}&ndash;present)\n\n}}\n'''Amir Jamal Garrett''' (born May 3, 1992) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Cincinnati Reds]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). Garrett was drafted by the Reds in 2011 but played [[college basketball]] for the [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball|St. John's Red Storm]] before pursuing a baseball career fully.\n\n==Early years==\nGarrett began his high school career at [[Sierra Vista High School (Spring Valley, Nevada)|Sierra Vista High School]] in [[Spring Valley, Nevada]], before he transferred to [[Leuzinger High School]] in [[Lawndale, California]], for his junior year. He transferred again, to Findlay College Prep in [[Henderson, Nevada]], for his senior year in 2010.<ref name=milb>{{cite web|last=Dykstra |first=Sam |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140515&content_id=75340930&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb |title=Reds' Garrett remains on two-sport path &#124; MiLB.com News &#124; The Official Site of Minor League Baseball |publisher=Milb.com |date=June 14, 2001 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=vmanstuff |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/jul/25/new-findlay-prep-player-amir-garrett-puts-show-aau/ |title=New Findlay Prep player Amir Garrett puts on a show at summer tourney \u2013 Las Vegas Sun News |publisher=Lasvegassun.com |date=July 25, 2010 |accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref> Findlay does not have a baseball team. His father convinced him to give baseball another chance, so he held a training session for [[Major League Baseball]] [[scout (sports)|scouts]], in which he threw a [[fastball]] upwards of {{convert|96|mph}}.<ref name=si/> Eligible in the [[2011 Major League Baseball draft]], the [[Cincinnati Reds]] selected Garrett in the 22nd round. He signed with the Reds, receiving a $1&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]] and permission to continue his basketball career.<ref name=nymag/> In the fall of 2011, Garrett enrolled at [[Bridgton Academy]] in Bridgton, Maine, where he played on the basketball team throughout the 2011-12 season, until enrolling at [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]].\n\n==College career==\n[[Image:Amir Garrett for the St. John's Red Storm.jpg|thumb|left|Garrett with [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball|St. John's]] in 2013]]\nHeading into college, Garrett was a four-star basketball recruit, ranked 68th in the country, and the 21st best [[small forward]].<ref name=nymag>{{cite web|last=Giles |first=Matt |url=https://nymag.com/daily/sports/2011/08/garrett-still-intends-to-play-for-st-john-s.html |title=Garrett Still Intends to Play for St. John's \u2013 The Sports Section |publisher=Nymag.com |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> Garrett committed to attend [[St. John's University (New York)|St. John's University]] to play [[college basketball]] for the [[St. John's Red Storm men's basketball]] team.<ref name=si>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/luke_winn/06/06/amir-garrett-st-johns-mlb/ |title=Findlay Prep's Amir Garrett choosing between St. John's, MLB - Luke Winn - SI.com |publisher=Sportsillustrated.cnn.com |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/basketball/mens/news/story?id=5816230 |title=EPSNU 100 SF Amir Garrett commits to St. John's. \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2010}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit  = [[Amir Garrett]]\n| position = [[Small forward|SF]]\n| hometown = Los Angeles{{!}}Los Angeles, CA\n| highschool = [[Bridgton Academy]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 6\n| weight = 190\n| 40     = \n| commitdate = 11/17/2010\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars    = 4\n| espn grade = 92\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit End\n| 40               = \n| year             = 2011\n| rivals ref title = St. John's Basketball Commitment List\n| scout ref title  = 2011 St. John's Basketball Commits\n| espn ref title   = ESPN\n| rivals school    = \n| scout s          = \n| espn schoolid    = \n| scout overall    = 72nd\n| rivals overall   = 68th\n| espn overall     = 99th\n| accessdate       = \n| bball            = yes}}\n\nGarrett was ruled ineligible to play for the college basketball team for the fall semester of his freshman year, in the [[2011\u201312 St. John's Red Storm men's basketball team|2011\u201312 season]], due to academic reasons. During that time, he spent the fall semester at Bridgton Academy in North Bridgton ME where he participated in the Fall Baseball program. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/ncb/story/_/id/6974420/st-john-3-players-ruled-ineligible-fall-semester |title=St. John's has 3 players ruled ineligible for fall semester \u2013 ESPN New York |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=September 15, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Greg Logan |url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/college/college-hoops-scoops-1.1620561/amir-garrett-s-growth-spurt-1.3545013 |title=Amir Garrett's growth spurt |publisher=Newsday.com |date=February 21, 2012 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> He was declared eligible in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmov.com/sports/baseball/national-league/136024623.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629144943/http://www.kmov.com/sports/baseball/national-league/136024623.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 29, 2013 |title=Garrett eligible for St. John's &#124; KMOV.com St. Louis |publisher=Kmov.com |date=December 22, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2013 }}</ref> As a freshman, Garrett played 26.9 [[minutes per game]].<ref name=nydn/> After the basketball season, Garrett played baseball for the [[Arizona Reds]] of the [[Rookie-level]] [[Arizona League]] and the [[Billings Mustangs]] of the [[Rookie-level]] [[Pioneer League (baseball)|Pioneer League]], pitching to a 4.05 [[earned run average]] (ERA) with 18 [[strikeout]]s and 13 [[base on balls|walks]] in 20 [[innings pitched]].<ref name=milb/>\n\nAs a sophomore, Garrett started 11 games, averaging 5.4 [[points per game]] and 4.3 [[rebounds per game]] in 20.1 minutes per game.<ref name=nydn/> After the [[2012\u201313 St. John's Red Storm men's basketball team|2012\u201313 college basketball season]], Garrett announced that he was leaving St. John's, with the intention of transferring to another college basketball team.<ref name=nydn>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/college/garrett-leaving-sju-hoops-possibly-pro-baseball-article-1.1306243 |title=Amir Garrett leaving St. John's basketball, Cincinnati Reds prospect could pursue pro baseball career |publisher=NY Daily News |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> He transferred to [[Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball|California State University, Northridge]],<ref>{{cite web|first=C. Trent |last=Rosecrans |url=http://cincinnati.com/blogs/reds/2013/05/08/reds-prospect-amir-garrett-to-continue-his-college-hoops-career/ |title=Reds prospect Amir Garrett to continue his college hoops career &#124; Cincinnati Reds |publisher=Cincinnati.com |date=May 8, 2013 |accessdate=May 16, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517151607/http://www2.cincinnati.com/blogs/reds/2013/05/08/reds-prospect-amir-garrett-to-continue-his-college-hoops-career/ |archivedate=May 17, 2014 }}</ref> and sat out the [[2013\u201314 Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball team|2013\u201314 season]] due to [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] transfer rules.<ref name=milb/> After \"[[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirting]]\" his first year, Garrett withdrew from the Matadors to pursue a pro baseball career.<ref>{{cite web|title=Two-sport star Amir Garrett gives up college hoops for pro baseball|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/two-sport-star-amir-garrett-gives-up-college-hoops-for-pro-baseball/|website=CBSSports.com|accessdate=September 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nGarrett began the 2013 baseball season with Billings, but was promoted to the [[Dayton Dragons]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Midwest League]] in July.<ref>{{cite web|author=MILB.com |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130719&content_id=54058674&fext=.jsp&vkey=pr_t459&sid=t459 |title=Two-Sport Athlete Amir Garrett Joins Dragons &#124; Dayton Dragons News |publisher=Milb.com |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> He finished the season with a 5.15 ERA, 32 strikeouts, and 26 walks in {{frac|57|2|3}} innings. He returned to Dayton for the start of the 2014 season.<ref name=milb/> In August 2014, Garrett decided to quit basketball and withdraw from Cal-State Northridge in order to focus on baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/eye-on-college-basketball/24653309/two-sport-star-amir-garrett-gives-up-college-hoops-for-pro-baseball|title=Two-sport star Amir Garrett gives up college hoops for pro baseball|first=Matt|last=Norlander |work=[[CBS Sports]]|date=August 8, 2014|accessdate=August 14, 2014}}</ref> He had a 7\u20138 record and a 3.65 ERA in 27 games started, and the Reds added him to their [[40-man roster]] after the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.reds.mlb.com/news/article/105793464/reds-prospect-amir-garrett-thriving-since-choosing-baseball-over-basketball|title=Prospect Garrett thriving since choosing baseball: Two-sport star happy with decision to put down basketball, commit to pitching|first=Mark|last=Sheldon|work=MLB.com|date=January 8, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> He began the 2015 season with the [[Daytona Tortugas]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]] (FSL),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/article/20150407/SPORTS/150409568|title=Former hoopster Amir Garrett flourishing after turning full attention to baseball|work=News-JournalOnline.com|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref> and was chosen to represent the Reds at the 2015 [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.reds.mlb.com/news/article/132835982/cincinnati-reds-trio-picked-for-futures-game|title=Cincinnati Reds trio picked for Futures Game|work=Cincinnati Reds|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Garrett finished the 2015 season with a 2.44 ERA and 133 strikeouts for Daytona, and with [[Jacob Faria]], was named the [[Florida State League Pitcher of the Year Award|Co-FSL Pitcher of the Year]].<ref name=pensacola/>\n\nGarrett opened the 2016 season with the [[Pensacola Blue Wahoos]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Southern League (baseball)|Southern League]].<ref name=pensacola>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160425&content_id=174509902&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb|title=Cincinnati Reds prospect Amir Garrett gets better as he goes along for Pensacola Blue Wahoos - MiLB.com News - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|work=MiLB.com|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> The Reds promoted him to the [[Louisville Bats]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[International League]] in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/mlb/reds/2016/06/18/notes-amir-garrett-earns-triple--promotion/86087740/|title=Notes: Amir Garrett earns Triple-A promotion|work=Cincinnati Enquirer|date=June 18, 2016|accessdate=October 17, 2016}}</ref> He was named to appear in the 2016 All-Star Futures Game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/mlb/reds/2016/06/28/notes-amir-garrett-selected-futures-game/86493498/|title=Notes: Amir Garrett selected for Futures Game|work=Cincinnati Enquirer|date=June 28, 2016|accessdate=October 17, 2016}}</ref> He finished 2016 with a 7-8 record and a 2.55 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=607237#/career/R/pitching/2016/ALL|title=Amir Garrett Stats, Highlights, Bio |work=MiLB.com Stats - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|accessdate=October 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGarrett made the Reds' [[Opening Day]] roster in 2017.<ref>http://m.mlb.com/news/article/221408612/amir-garrett-elated-about-making-reds-rotation/</ref> In his Major league debut on April 7 against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Garrett went six shutout innings, giving up just two hits and earning the win in the Reds 2&ndash;0 victory over the Cardinals.\n\nOn May 7, 2017 Garrett was optioned down to Reds AAA affiliate [[Louisville Bats]], RHP Barrett Astin was recalled.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gray|first1=Doug|title=Amir Garrett optioned to Triple-A, recall Barrett Astin|url=http://redsminorleagues.com/2017/05/07/amir-garrett-optioned-triple-recall-barrett-astin/|website=RedsMinorLeagues.com|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref> On May 25, 2017, Garrett was placed on the 10-day disabled list due to right hip inflammation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheldon|first1=Mark|title=Amir Garrett on DL with right hip inflammation|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/232390664/reds-put-pitcher-amir-garrett-on-disabled-list/|publisher=MLB|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref> Garrett was optioned and recalled multiple times during the season. In 14 starts for Louisville he was 2-4 with a 5.72 ERA, and in 16 games (14 starts) for Cincinnati, he compiled a 3-8 record and 7.39 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=607237#/career/R/pitching/2018/ALL|title=Amir Garrett Stats, Highlights, Bio - MiLB.com Stats - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|publisher=MiLB.com|accessdate=May 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGarrett began the 2018 season in the Cincinnati bullpen. In 66 games, he was 1-2 with 71 strikeouts in 63 innings.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn an April 7, 2019 game against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], Garrett was ejected after his role in a bench clearing incident involving [[Chris Archer]], [[Derek Dietrich]], [[Yasiel Puig]], [[David Bell (baseball)|David Bell]], [[Keone Kela]], and [[Felipe V\u00e1zquez]]. Over 3 months later, on July 30 Garrett was once again involved in a bench clearing incident, charging the Pirates dugout and throwing punches at players in the dugout. Garrett was ejected along with Yasiel Puig, [[Francisco Cervelli]], [[Kyle Crick]], Chris Archer, and [[Trevor Williams (baseball)|Trevor Williams]]. This followed after David Bell (who would later go back onto the field during the brawl) was ejected in the bottom of the 8th inning by Larry Vanover for arguing balls and strikes and later in the top of the 9th inning where Reds relief pitcher Jared Hughes and bench coach Freddie Benavides were ejected in the ninth for hitting [[Starling Marte]] with his first pitch.{{cn|date=July 2019}} On August 1, 2019, Garrett was suspended for 8 games.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of multi-sport athletes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=607237|espn=33652|br=g/garream01|fangraphs=14375|brm=garret000ami}}\n*{{Twitter|Amir_Garrett|CountOnAG}}\n*{{Instagram|amir_garrett|CountOnAG}}\n\n{{Cincinnati Reds roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrett, Amir}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:People from Victorville, California]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from California]]\n[[Category:African-American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Findlay Prep alumni]]\n[[Category:St. John's Red Storm men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Reds players]]\n[[Category:Billings Mustangs players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Dayton Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Daytona Tortugas players]]\n[[Category:Pensacola Blue Wahoos players]]\n[[Category:Louisville Bats players]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n", "name_user": "2601:40